    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey i am studying for my civil eng exam and i'm a bit stuck on reinforced concrete. basically i get why concrete is good for compression but why do we actually need to add the steel rebar inside it?? like what is the actual relationship between the compressive strength of the concrete and the tensile strength of the steel in a foundation slab?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Concrete is exceptionally strong in compression but very weak in tension, whereas steel rebar has high tensile strength and excellent ductility. When combined, they act compositely to share loads: the concrete carries the compression forces while the embedded steel resists the tensile stresses and flexural bending moments that would otherwise cause cracking. This complementary relationship allows structures like foundation slabs to be both rigid and flexible enough to withstand complex real-world loading conditions.",
      "source": "target",
