      "content": "The bond between the rebar and concrete is indeed one of your most critical exam concepts, as any gap gathering moisture or chemicals will eventually weaken it. While these gaps seem too small for large objects, they can absorb water, which leads to corrosion of the steel and expansive rust pushing the bar out of the cover or cracking the concrete. To prevent this in real-world structures, engineers intentionally place \"blinking\" or incidental cover (or stirrups) and ensure the concrete is properly air-entrained and protected to maintain that grip over decades.",
